      "url": "https://www.misoenergy.org/engage/stakeholder-feedback/2025/pac-eras-proposal-pac-2023-1-20250219/",
      "title": "PAC: ERAS Proposal (PAC-2023-1) (20250219)",
      "published_date": "2025-02-19T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "PAC: ERAS Proposal (PAC-2023-1) (20250219)\n\nSkip to main content Skip to footer\n\n# PAC: ERAS Proposal (PAC-2023-1) (20250219)\n\nItem Expired\n\n##### Related Entity(s):\n\nPlanning Advisory Committee (PAC)\n\n##### Topic(s):\n\nGenerator Interconnection\n\n---\n\nIn the February 19, 2025, meeting of the Planning Advisory Committee (PAC), MISO presented the latest Expedited Resource Addition Study (ERAS) proposal. Stakeholders are asked to evaluate the Tariff redlines based on the principles outlined in the presentation for feedback by March 3.\n\n---\n\n### Submitted Feedback\n\nSubmit Feedback\n\n#### Stone Pigman LLC Submitted by Noel Darce\n\n### Posted - 03/04/2025\n\nThe LPSC Staff feedback is being sent as an attachment to an email from Noel Darce to stakeholder relations dated March 3. We approve posting the attachment to the feedback site.\n\n#### Public Service Commission of Wisconsin Submitted by Ryan Kohler\n\n### Posted - 03/04/2025\n\nFeedback by Public Service Commission of Wisconsin (PSCW) Office of Regional Markets (ORM) Staff to MISO on PAC: ERAS Proposal (PAC-2023-1) (20250219) Tariff Redlines:\n\nWe acknowledge that unique circumstances, including new large load additions seeking to come online more rapidly than generation may adequately support and extremely delayed generation queue study times, is driving the proposed ERAS process. However, as expressed in our comments submitted through the Organization of MISO States (OMS) on 2/5/25, Wisconsin has unaddressed concerns regarding the proposals disconnect between stated need and generator online dates as well as the effect of the current ERAS proposal could have on regulatory bodies.\n\nWe urge continued focus on the existing queue and alternative MISO processes that can be used to address urgent resource adequacy needs.\n\nMISO adopted some of OMS’s drafted RERRA acknowledgement language but Wisconsin urges MISO to change their draft Tariff language to reflect OMS’s drafted language verbatim. As written, the section 3.9.1 redlines read, “…address a reliability and/or resource adequacy need identified by the RERRA\" instead of OMS’s, “resource should be considered for the ERAS process in order to meet a resource adequacy need that the state or LSE (or IC, where appropriate) has claimed.” MISO’s proposed language would force a regulatory body to have formally made its determination of need for a resource prior to approving its entrance into ERAS. While this may be the approach that some RERRAs take, the MISO proposal should avoid a requirement that states have either already made their determination of need or RERRAs could be guilty of pre-judging a project’s merit (here, a resource adequacy need) before proper review and analysis is conducted during the regulatory process. We are encouraged to hear that MISO is working with OMS to change this language back to OMS’s recommendation to address potential RERRA concerns.\n\nWisconsin is also concerned about a potential disconnect on the apparent urgent resource adequacy need of ERAS and the arbitrary nature of the commercial operation dates (CODs) as allowed in MISO’s revised proposal. If ERAS is needed to allow generation to meet urgent resource adequacy needs, then a COD date of 2032 for 2025/26 ERAS projects does not seem consistent with this need. Wisconsin continues to support a smaller window for ERAS eligibility as the primary method to limit unnecessary harms to generators in the queue and utilities that are not utilizing ERAS. A clean COD requirement by 12/31/28 with the default three-year auto-extension is much more likely to be approved by FERC and even more in line with the stated need for urgency.\n\n#### Alliant Energy Submitted by Shivam Sharma\n\n### Posted - 03/04/2025\n\nAlliant Energy is pleased to provide feedback on the Expedited Resource Addition Study (ERAS). We commend MISO's proactive approach to addressing the current capacity concerns and the backlog in the generation interconnection queue. The primary reason for creating this process is to ensure resource adequacy, which is crucial for maintaining a reliable energy supply. The ERAS proposal's focus on expediting the approval process for new generation projects meeting a strict criterion is a significant step forward, as it will help in addressing resource adequacy issues more swiftly.\n\nWe particularly appreciate the individual project evaluation approach, which allows for more tailored assessments and quicker decision-making. Additionally, the stringent requirements for site control, milestone payments, and state acknowledgment ensure that only serious and well-backed projects move forward, maintaining the integrity of the process. These measures, along with the inclusion of both Load Serving Entities (LSEs) and Interconnection Customers (ICs) with executed Power Purchase Agreements (PPAs), will undoubtedly enhance the efficiency of the project approval process and contribute to a more reliable energy landscape. Importantly, we believe this process will not negatively impact existing que projects, as they too will benefit from any improvements to infrastructure made as a result of ERAS projects.\n\nAlliant Energy does not support the suggestion that projects may not be withdrawn from ERAS on the basis of the magnitude of Network Upgrades needed to interconnect. We believe this approach does not support rational decision making and is not in the best interest of retail customers as it places customers at risk for unnecessary transmission costs. Additionally, reducing project completion time frames by removing the standard 3-year extension on an expected COD in a GIA could compromise the effectiveness and reliability of the process. We are also strongly against the suggestion for MISO to consider if other projects in the queue could be used to meet a resource adequacy need. This suggestion would give MISO a resource planning role which we feel is most appropriate to be kept with states or the Relevant Electric Retail Authority (RERRA).\n\nOverall, the ERAS proposal is a promising initiative that can significantly improve the efficiency of the interconnection process for critical resources and address resource adequacy concerns. It is essential to keep the proposal consistent with how MISO has presented thus far, to ensure that LSEs can meet their resource adequacy requirements and satisfy the obligation to serve new large load customers effectively. Alliant Energy fully supports this proposal and looks forward to seeing its positive impact on the energy sector. Thank you for considering our feedback.\n\nSincerely,\n\nAlliant Energy\n\n#### Entergy Submitted by Samson Mabry IV\n\n### Posted - 03/04/2025\n\nThe Entergy Operating Companies (EOC or Entergy)[1], in response to the latest ERAS proposal presented at the February 19th PAC meeting, submit the following comments:\n\nEntergy views the ERAS Proposal as a necessary and critical solution to address imminent forecasted capacity shortfalls to serve load. Entergy unequivocally supports MISO’s new proposal and commends MISO on its efforts to address the concerns of the retail regulators regarding the need for additional capacity. Entergy also recognizes the compromise MISO has struck between setting firm commercial operation date requirements while ensuring interconnection customers retain the flexibility to bring necessary resources online as quickly as possible in light of supply chain and permitting uncertainties that exist in the current environment.\n\nEntergy encourages MISO to maintain the flexibility built into the RERRA acknowledgement but asks that MISO offer language that can assuage regulatory concerns on prejudging the outcome of projects that qualify for ERAS. For example, in its redlines, MISO could note in Attachment X, section 3.9.1 of the tariff that “Nothing in the RERRA acknowledgment shall prejudge the outcome of any RERRA-conducted regulatory proceeding.”\n\n---\n\n[1] The Entergy Operating Companies are Entergy Arkansas, LLC, Entergy Louisiana, LLC, Ente",
